00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:31.060
There are twelve chapters in the book,
and those show the twelve chapters.

00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:36.949
They're nearly all a scientific question,
like who was was the first person, what is

00:04:36.949 --> 00:04:40.759
the sun, what is a rainbow.

00:04:40.759 --> 00:04:45.710
Every chapter begins with myths from around
the world in answer

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:49.600
to the question and then goes on to the meat
of the chapter,

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:55.550
Which is the scientific answer what really
is the sun, what really is a rainbow,

00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:59.419
what really is an earthquake, and so on.

00:04:59.419 --> 00:05:04.569
The title, The Magic of Reality, I need to
clarify the word magic.

00:05:04.569 --> 00:05:09.490
I see the word magic is used in three different
senses.

00:05:09.490 --> 00:05:14.639
The first kind of magic is fairy tale spells,
fairy godmothers

00:05:14.639 --> 00:05:19.800
waving a wand
and turning a pumpkin into a coach or a frog

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:23.150
turning into a prince, that kind of thing.

00:05:23.150 --> 00:05:25.000
Nobody believes in that kind of magic.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.039
The second kind of magic is stage magic, conjuring.

00:05:29.039 --> 00:05:32.840
In America,
conjurors are called magicians but everybody

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:35.610
knows,
of course, that what conjurors do is only

00:05:35.610 --> 00:05:42.050
a trick although it looks like are real magic,
it looks like something supernatural.

00:05:42.050 --> 00:05:45.440
And the third kind of magic is the one that
I am really most keen on,

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:49.099
and the title of my book, which is the magic
of reality.

00:05:49.099 --> 00:05:53.180
When we're moved to tears by a beautiful piece
of music we describe

00:05:53.180 --> 00:05:55.349
it as magical.

00:05:55.349 --> 00:05:59.340
Or we look up at the stars,
we look up at the Milky Way and we say what

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:01.530
a magical sight.

00:06:01.530 --> 00:06:04.460
The whole of science, the whole of what science
reveals it

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:09.440
seems to me
is magical in that sense, not supernatural,

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:16.830
but fills one with a sense of wonder, a sort
of swelling of the chest which one

00:06:16.830 --> 00:06:19.509
can describe as magical.

00:06:19.509 --> 00:06:26.249
The purpose of my book is to show that reality,
the facts of reality, as understood through

00:06:26.249 --> 00:06:32.960
science, is magical in this third
sense, the poetic sense, the 'good to be alive'

00:06:32.960 --> 00:06:34.400
sense.

00:06:34.400 --> 00:06:40.539
Now, I said that nobody believes in supernatural
magic, nobody believes in fairies

00:06:40.539 --> 00:06:44.381
turning pumpkins into coaches, and frogs into
princes.

00:06:44.381 --> 00:06:50.651
And I want to make the point,
a really rather important point, it's actually

00:06:50.651 --> 00:06:55.889
not just that no one has ever actually seen
a frog turn into prince, there are very

00:06:55.889 --> 00:07:00.219
good reasons for saying it will never happen,
it's impossible.

00:07:00.219 --> 00:07:04.539
And it is important to understand that, in
order to understand how it is

00:07:04.539 --> 00:07:09.909
that frogs and princes and kangaroos and tigers
came into existence at all because they did

00:07:09.909 --> 00:07:12.259
not come into existence by magic, of
course.

00:07:12.259 --> 00:07:15.689
They came into existence by evolution.

00:07:15.689 --> 00:07:23.750
So why is it that things can't magically turn
into other things from one magic blow?

00:07:23.750 --> 00:07:25.949
Why can't frogs turn into princes?

00:07:25.949 --> 00:07:28.539
Why can't pumpkins turn into coaches?

00:07:28.539 --> 00:07:37.470
Well, the reason is, frogs and princes, and
pumpkins and coaches are all complicated things.

00:07:37.470 --> 00:07:42.449
And complicated means statistically improbable.

00:07:42.449 --> 00:07:48.580
And statistically improbable means that
it isn't going to just happen by luck.

00:07:48.580 --> 00:07:56.340
So if you imagine making the task for our
fairy godmother, making a coach by magic a

00:07:56.340 --> 00:07:59.009
little bit easier,
well imagine that instead of giving her a

00:07:59.009 --> 00:08:05.449
pumpkin to start with,
we give her a sort of IKEA kit for making

00:08:05.449 --> 00:08:06.620
a coach.

00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:09.400
It comes in a box, and she takes all the bits
in the box,

00:08:09.400 --> 00:08:13.110
puts them in a great big sack and shakes them,
and shakes them,

00:08:13.110 --> 00:08:18.740
and shakes them for a billion years, and every
time she shakes she looks to see whether a

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:20.900
coach has tumbled out.

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:25.990
And of course it won't, not in a trillion
years, it won't.

00:08:25.990 --> 00:08:32.450
Coaches, and princes, and frogs, and us, and
aardvarks, and dinosaurs

00:08:32.450 --> 00:08:38.010
are all much too complicated to happen by
chance.

00:08:38.010 --> 00:08:40.310
So how did they happen?

00:08:40.310 --> 00:08:46.540
Oh, first of all, I should say that in some
cases we can calculate the odds against happening

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:47.670
by chance.

00:08:47.670 --> 00:08:54.260
If we're playing cards and we deal thirteen
cards to each of four players

00:08:54.260 --> 00:09:00.250
as you would in Bridge and imagine that I
pick up my cards,

00:09:00.250 --> 00:09:05.570
I pick up my thirteen cards and I gasped in
astonishment because I've got the perfect

00:09:05.570 --> 00:09:09.030
hand of all spades.

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:13.200
So I lay down my cards on the table and I
say no good going on with the game

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:18.540
I've obviously won this game because I've
got a perfect hand, and then to my amazement,

00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:22.660
one by one the other three players
lay down their hands and somebody's got all

00:09:22.660 --> 00:09:27.800
the diamonds, somebody's got all the clubs,
somebody's got all the hearts.

00:09:27.800 --> 00:09:30.830
Well,
that could happen.

00:09:30.830 --> 00:09:32.440
What are the odds against it?

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:35.780
Well, you all have worked out in your head
[Laughter]

00:09:35.780 --> 00:09:57.380
that the odds against that are 536,447,737,765,488,792,839,237,442,000
against.

00:09:57.380 --> 00:10:04.250
However the particular deal is no less likely
than any other particular deal is,

00:10:04.250 --> 00:10:09.310
just that we notice, we notice it because
there's something special about it.

00:10:09.310 --> 00:10:14.910
You could arbitrarily designate any particular
deal and say the odds against that happening

00:10:14.910 --> 00:10:20.150
are also that number of
octillions, etcetera.

00:10:20.150 --> 00:10:22.640
By the way,
once I was reading that out while giving a

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:26.280
lecture in America,
and they have a rule there that you have to

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:31.530
have someone standing at the side of the stage
doing sign language so I couldn't

00:10:31.530 --> 00:10:36.350
help stealing a look at her while I was doing
all this.

00:10:36.350 --> 00:10:40.910
[laughter]
And I also, this is only totally an aside

00:10:40.910 --> 00:10:43.881
now,
but I also during the same lecture had an

00:10:43.881 --> 00:10:50.440
occasion to refer
to the Large Hadron Collider in Geneva and

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:54.340
I was talking about how moved I was when I
went to visit the Large Hadron Collider

00:10:54.340 --> 00:11:01.380
and I told as an aside the story that in the
first edition of one of my books, this was

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:05.790
misprinted as Large Hard on Collider,
[laugher]

00:11:05.790 --> 00:11:12.330
and I, again, have to look at this woman and
see how she was--.[laughter]

00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:21.890
Anyway, as I was saying, in the case of a
perfect bridge, of a perfect deal in bridge,

00:11:21.890 --> 00:11:24.510
you can calculate the odds against it.

00:11:24.510 --> 00:11:27.360
You can't calculate the odds of shaking up
the bits

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:31.800
of a prince, or shaking up the bits of a frog
and getting a prince,

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:36.330
but it's going to be just as high, just as
unlikely.

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:40.080
Probably even more so than getting a perfect
hand in bridge.

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:47.840
So how do
we get tigers and kangaroos and frogs and

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:49.370
princes?

00:11:49.370 --> 00:11:56.780
The answer is it certainly does not come about
by chance, it comes about by the nonrandom

00:11:56.780 --> 00:12:00.080
process,
of evolution by natural selection.

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:06.330
The key to understanding that is that although
there is chance involved, there is luck

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:11.440
involved,
it's a very small amount of luck in each step

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:12.760
of the way.

00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:16.480
The point is
that there are millions of steps of the way,

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:22.070
one after the other through an immense amount
of geological time and each one of

00:12:22.070 --> 00:12:29.190
those tiny steps means that a frog, for example,
turns into a slightly different kind of frog,

00:12:29.190 --> 00:12:30.671
and then a slightly different kind of frog
again,

00:12:30.671 --> 00:12:32.950
and a slightly different kind of frog again.

00:12:32.950 --> 00:12:39.350
Each of those tiny steps is not improbable,
is not a wildly improbable thing

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:43.290
like shaking the bits of a frog and getting
a prince.

00:12:43.290 --> 00:12:48.440
It's because there are so many steps, it's
because the luck is smeared out

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:53.970
into gradual steps that it works and that's
why we've been able to go from some kind of

00:12:53.970 --> 00:12:59.930
bacterial ancestor three billion
years ago to all the different kinds of animal

00:12:59.930 --> 00:13:03.500
and plant that we see today.

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:12.650
Now, â€¦ [pause] I'm now going to take the
first, take the next chapter, chapter two,

00:13:12.650 --> 00:13:17.420
which is the first of the chapters that follows
the plan of having a question

00:13:17.420 --> 00:13:20.870
followed by myths followed by the true scientific
answer.

00:13:20.870 --> 00:13:26.760
And the question of this chapter is who was
the first person?

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:31.870
And, as you know,
this has been the subject of many myths,

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:37.320
and a particularly familiar myth is the Hebrew
myth of Adam and Eve,

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:41.700
the Jewish myth of Adam and Eve, which has
been adopted by Christians and by Muslims,

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:43.590
as you know.

00:13:43.590 --> 00:13:51.940
And just to give you another myth, the myth
of Odin, the Norse myth,

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:53.470
which is just a quite separate myth.

00:13:53.470 --> 00:14:00.750
And there are thousands of origin myths
which account for the who was the first person.

00:14:00.750 --> 00:14:04.200
They're all colorful,
they're all nice stories but they're, of course,

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:05.380
not true.

00:14:05.380 --> 00:14:11.160
And we're now going to come onto the true
answer to the question who was the first person.

00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:12.740
The scientific answer.

00:14:12.740 --> 00:14:18.740
Well, this may surprise you there never was
a first person.

00:14:18.740 --> 00:14:23.030
Because every person had to have parents and
they had to have parents,

00:14:23.030 --> 00:14:25.100
and they had to have parents, and so on.

00:14:25.100 --> 00:14:30.860
And the same is true of rabbits and crocodiles
and, and, and lizards and everything.

00:14:30.860 --> 00:14:35.110
Every animal ever born, every creature ever
born belonged

00:14:35.110 --> 00:14:44.440
to the same species as its parents and its
children, and its grandparents and its great

00:14:44.440 --> 00:14:46.420
grandparents.

00:14:46.420 --> 00:14:47.860
How far back can we take that?

00:14:47.860 --> 00:14:50.270
Can we take about forever?

00:14:50.270 --> 00:14:52.560
No, obviously we can't.

00:14:52.560 --> 00:15:00.070
Um, and this is the main lesson I want to
reach in this part of my talk.

00:15:00.070 --> 00:15:07.230
Even though every species ever born is the
same species as its parents and its children,

00:15:07.230 --> 00:15:11.810
nevertheless, if you go back a sufficiently
large number of generations, then you come

00:15:11.810 --> 00:15:14.660
to something very different.

00:15:14.660 --> 00:15:19.570
So let's do a thought experiment.

00:15:19.570 --> 00:15:21.660
Imagine that you take up, a thought experiment
is an experiment

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:24.830
you don't actually do, you just imagine.

00:15:24.830 --> 00:15:32.170
Imagine that you take a picture of yourself
and put on top of it a picture of your father,

00:15:32.170 --> 00:15:35.730
then on top of that, his father, and then
his father, and then his father,

00:15:35.730 --> 00:15:41.610
and then his father
and build a gigantic skyscraper of pictures

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:44.250
going backwards in time.

00:15:44.250 --> 00:15:46.120
How far back should we go?

00:15:46.120 --> 00:15:52.851
Well, I think we should go back 185,000,000
greats so I am going to go back to your one

00:15:52.851 --> 00:15:57.630
hundred
eighty-five million greats grandfather.

00:15:57.630 --> 00:16:01.380
How high would that skyscraper be?

00:16:01.380 --> 00:16:06.950
It would be more than one hundred eighty New
York skyscrapers

00:16:06.950 --> 00:16:09.170
piled on top of each other.

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:11.570
So we're going back quite a long way.

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:13.670
Obviously that skyscraper would simply fall
over, it's much

00:16:13.670 --> 00:16:14.880
too high.

00:16:14.880 --> 00:16:19.130
So let's tip it
on its side and put the pictures all the way

00:16:19.130 --> 00:16:21.290
along a great big long bookshelf.

00:16:21.290 --> 00:16:25.700
How long would that bookshelf be?

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:27.170
About forty
miles.

00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:34.950
So the near end of the bookshelf has a picture
of you, the far end of the bookshelf has a

00:16:34.950 --> 00:16:41.360
picture of your one hundred
eighty-five million greats grandfather.

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:44.530
What did he look like?

00:16:44.530 --> 00:16:49.430
Was he an old man with wispy hair and side
whiskers?

00:16:49.430 --> 00:16:52.590
Was he a cave man in a leopard skin?

00:16:52.590 --> 00:16:55.120
No, forget any such thought.

00:16:55.120 --> 00:16:57.990
Your one hundred eighty-five million greats
grandfather

00:16:57.990 --> 00:17:04.319
looked something like that.

00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:08.699
Your one hundred eighty-five million greats
grandfather was a fish.

00:17:08.699 --> 00:17:11.709
[laughter]
So was your one hundred eighty-five million

00:17:11.709 --> 00:17:17.559
greats grandmother which is just as well.

00:17:17.559 --> 00:17:27.111
If we now walk along our forty mile long bookshelf,
we can pull off pictures now and again

00:17:27.111 --> 00:17:28.890
to see how we're going.

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:35.470
Every picture shows a creature belonging to
the same species as it's immediate neighbors

00:17:35.470 --> 00:17:38.259
on the
shelf.

00:17:38.259 --> 00:17:43.850
Yet if you go back sufficiently far,
where your four thousand greats grandfather

00:17:43.850 --> 00:17:46.220
is, who you see there looks pretty much like
us,

00:17:46.220 --> 00:17:50.970
your fifty thousand greats grandfather looks
just a bit different.

00:17:50.970 --> 00:17:53.750
He would have been perhaps a member of the
species homo

00:17:53.750 --> 00:18:01.320
Erectus,
not the same species as us, but pretty similar,

00:18:01.320 --> 00:18:03.480
nevertheless.

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:07.879
Imagine that we take a time machine and we
ride backwards in time

00:18:07.879 --> 00:18:11.059
and we go back in steps of ten thousand years.

00:18:11.059 --> 00:18:15.690
If every step of ten thousand years, we get
out of our time machine,

00:18:15.690 --> 00:18:21.240
and we look around and we see which of our
great, great, great, great grandparents we

00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:22.990
can see.

